        <h2 id="how-to-increase">How to increase watch time</h2>
        <p>Increasing watch time requires action at three stages: before the view (getting the right viewer), during the video (retaining them), and after the video (keeping them on the channel).</p>

        <h3>Before the view: attract the right viewers</h3>
        <p>The biggest source of low AVD is mismatched expectations. If your thumbnail or title promises something your video doesn't deliver, viewers leave within the first 30 seconds. Write titles and create thumbnails that accurately represent the video — attracting viewers who genuinely want what you're delivering.</p>

        <h3>During the video: retain attention</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Strong hook in the first 30 seconds.</strong> State what the viewer will learn and why it matters. Viewers decide whether to stay or leave within the first 30 seconds.</li>
          <li><strong>Pattern interrupts every 90-120 seconds.</strong> A change in pace, a new visual, a question, or a surprising statement prevents attention drift.</li>
          <li><strong>Cut ruthlessly.</strong> Remove anything that doesn't advance the story or deliver value. Dead air, excessive intros, and off-topic tangents are the primary causes of retention drops.</li>
          <li><strong>Tease upcoming content.</strong> "Coming up in a few minutes, I'll show you the one setting that doubled my results" — keeps viewers watching to see the payoff.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>After the video: extend the session</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>End screens with a related video.</strong> Suggest the most relevant next video with a visual end screen in the last 20 seconds.</li>
          <li><strong>Cards at peak engagement.</strong> Add info cards to relevant timestamps where viewers are still highly engaged, pointing to related videos.</li>
          <li><strong>Playlists.</strong> Organise content into thematic playlists. YouTube's algorithm gives extra credit for videos that sustain a viewing session within a playlist.</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Watch time vs view count trap</div>
          <p>Never optimise purely for views at the expense of watch time. A thumbnail that generates clicks but disappoints viewers trains the algorithm to recommend your video less. A video with 10,000 views and 60% AVD will outperform a video with 50,000 views and 10% AVD in long-term algorithmic reach.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common watch time mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Long intros before value delivery</strong> — the audience retention graph shows a predictable cliff in the first 30 seconds. Get to the content immediately.</li>
          <li><strong>Misleading thumbnails</strong> — they attract the wrong viewers who leave quickly, tanking AVD.</li>
          <li><strong>No end screen or cards</strong> — missing the opportunity to extend session duration costs channel-level watch time.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring audience retention analytics</strong> — the retention graph shows exactly where viewers drop off. Those drop-off points are the highest-leverage editing improvement targets.</li>
          <li><strong>Very short videos for long topics</strong> — a 2-minute video covering a topic that deserves 10 minutes cannot accumulate meaningful watch time even with perfect retention.</li>
        </ul>

