          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does watch time affect YouTube SEO?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes, directly. YouTube's algorithm uses watch time as its primary signal for deciding which videos to recommend in search results, the homepage, and the suggested feed. Videos that accumulate high watch time relative to their age and subscribers are given broader algorithmic distribution — the core mechanism of YouTube growth.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is the difference between watch time and average view duration?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Watch time is an absolute metric — total minutes watched across all viewers. Average view duration (AVD) is a relative metric — average minutes watched per view. Both matter: watch time signals total audience engagement; AVD signals how compelling the content is to individuals. A viral video with low AVD tells the algorithm the content disappointed viewers despite attracting clicks.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
